| Recognizing Your Own Handwriting As A Password                     |
|   from the sounds-suspiciously-like-reading dept.                  |
|   posted by CmdrTaco on Monday July 02, @08:44 (Security)          |
|   http://it.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/07/02/1215203           |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]Gary writes "A new online authentication system [1]called Dynahand
could make logging in to websites a little easier. With Dynahand, users
simply identify their own handwriting, instead of entering a cryptic
password or buying a biometric device to scan their fingerprints. The
user's handwriting samples contain only digits, since numerals are harder
for an outside party to recognize than letters are. The digits displayed
are random, so the handwriting is the only clue to the correct answer."

Discuss this story at:
    http://it.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/07/02/1215203

Links:
    0. mailto:garethm85@gmail.com
    1. http://www.newlaunches.com/archives/dynahand_new_age_handwritten_passwords.php


