| Are Contactless Payments Really Secure?                            |
|   from the tin-foil-pants dept.                                    |
|   posted by ScuttleMonkey on Monday July 02, @16:31 (Security)     |
|   http://it.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/07/02/2014243           |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]berberine writes to tell us Ars Technica has a closer look at whether
the RFID technology behind many of the up and coming "contactless payment
systems" is robust enough to [1]prevent account fraud and the theft of
personal information. "Concerns over the security of contactless systems
were heightened last week by a Federal Reserve decision that will allow
for even more casual, low-cost purchases to be made across the country.
In recent years, credit card companies have waived their signature
requirements for so-called "small ticket" items in order to get a slice
of the action. Visa, for instance, doesn't require your signature for
purchases at or below $25."

